{
  "id": "phekb-nafld-labs",
  "source": "phekb",
  "source_id": "nafld",
  "name": "NAFLD - Elevated ALT/AST Lab Query",
  "description": "Tests ability to find NAFLD patients via elevated liver enzymes. ALT (alanine aminotransferase) and AST (aspartate aminotransferase) are the standard liver function tests. ALT >40 IU/L is the traditional cutoff for liver injury (modern guidelines suggest >25-30 for women and >35 for men). NAFLD typically presents with ALT > AST (ratio inverted from alcoholic liver disease where AST > ALT). Synthea generates ALT 60-200 IU/L for active NAFLD patients.",
  "prompt": "Find patients with elevated liver enzyme lab results including alanine aminotransferase (ALT) or aspartate aminotransferase (AST) greater than 40 IU/L.",
  "prompts": {
    "naive": "Find patients with high liver enzymes.",
    "broad": "Find patients with elevated liver function tests — alanine aminotransferase (ALT) or aspartate aminotransferase (AST) values greater than 40 IU/L, the traditional clinical threshold for liver injury workup.",
    "expert": "I need to find NAFLD patients via elevated liver enzymes, using Observation resources. Search for both alanine aminotransferase and aspartate aminotransferase results, each with their respective LOINC codes. Apply a value-quantity filter requiring a result greater than forty international units per liter — the traditional upper limit of normal for both enzymes. These liver function tests are cross-indicated for many conditions beyond NAFLD (hepatitis, drug-induced liver injury, alcohol use disorder), so a labs-only cohort will include patients with liver injury from other causes."
  },
